	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Public consultation launched on EU trade policy</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 July 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC has launched a public consultation on the future of the EU’s trade policy. The aim of the public consultation is to gather views on the ‘rationale, scope and strategic objectives for a future EU trade policy’. The consultation will run from 2 June to 28 July 2010 and is open to all stakeholders within the EU and in third countries. The EC intends to set out its policy proposals during the autumn of 2010 ‘explaining how trade policy can help achieve the objectives of the Europe 2020 Strategy’. There are some 30 questions tabled under 10 major headings. A number of these questions would appear to be directly relevant to future ACP-EU trade relations. </p><p>By way of introduction the question is posed: ‘now that the new Lisbon Treaty has entered into force, how can we best ensure that our future trade policy is coherent with the EU’s external action as a whole, and notably in relation to the EU’s neighbouring countries?’ The EC highlights in its background paper the principle policy focus: ‘stimulating growth, creating jobs and increasing prosperity for EU citizens’. It notes how in recent decades this has been built on consolidating the single internal market and economic integration within the EU, and ‘open markets at home and abroad for trade and investment’. It highlights the links between the EU’s prosperity and ‘the markets of other countries and regions, many of which enjoy much faster economic growth’.</p><p>The background paper highlights the increasing globalisation of supply chains, with two-thirds of EU imports being inputs into other products. In the context of globalising supply chains, the shifting of the global economic focus of power to large emerging economies and the lessons emerging from the economic downturn, the questions are posed:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘Given the importance of boosting growth, creating more jobs and ensuring a more resource-efficient and greener economy, how can EU trade policy help?’ </li>

<li>‘What should the new trade priorities be in the light of the Europe 2020 Strategy?’</li>

</ul>
<p>At the level of the WTO the question is posed:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘In addition to continuing to push for a successful conclusion to the Doha Round, how can the EU best pursue overall EU trade policy objectives in the WTO?’</li>

</ul>
<p>On bilateral trade negotiations, the questions are posed:</p>
<ul>

<li>Do current EU FTA negotiations ‘provide the right geographic and substantive focus for [EU] bilateral trade relationships in the context of the Europe 2020 strategy?’ </li>

<li>Should the EU now try for closer economic integration and cooperation with larger, more important trade partners, including ‘overcoming regulatory differences that may have the effect of barriers to trade, and deepening our trade’?</li>

<li>‘How can the EU promote the establishment of and greater recourse to international standards without compromising legitimate public policy choices?’ </li>

<li>‘How can the EU, and in particular trade policy, help to secure a reliable and sustainable supply of raw materials by third countries?’</li>

</ul>
<p>On the issue of sustainable trade the questions are posed:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘How can trade policy best support green and inclusive growth around the globe, including through Sustainability Impact Assessments?’</li>

<li>‘Given the forthcoming revision of the Common Agricultural Policy and the continuing need to foster a sustainable agricultural sector in Europe, how should EU trade policy develop in this area consistently with the overall objectives of the Lisbon Treaty?’</li>

</ul>
<p>The importance of avoiding ‘green protectionism is recognised, while it is stressed that possible negative environmental and social effects of trade should be ‘appropriately addressed’.</p><p>On the issue of the link between trade and development the questions are posed:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘How can the EU best strengthen the issue of trade and development in its trade policy?’ </li>

<li>‘Should the EU pursue a more differentiated approach in its trade relations to reflect the level of development of particular partners?’ </li>

<li>‘How should the EU approach the issue of trade preferences in relation to the generally low level of EU Most Favoured Nation (MFN) tariffs, which will further be eroded following the possible conclusion of the Doha Round?’</li>

</ul>
<p>On the issue of enforcement of agreements and dealing with unfair practices, the EC poses the questions:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘How can the EU best safeguard its firms or interests against trading partners who do not play by the rules?’ </li>

<li>‘Are the existing tools and priorities sufficient to address unfair competition from third countries?’ </li>

<li>‘How can the EU best safeguard its firms or interests against major trading partners who maintain an asymmetric level of openness and resort to protectionist measures?’ </li>

<li>‘Are the existing tools and priorities sufficient to address practices such as keeping EU suppliers out of government procurement markets, market access restrictions, restricted and insecure access to energy and raw materials?’ </li>

<li>‘What else can EU trade policy do to further improve the protection of IPR in key markets?’</li>

</ul>
<p>The EC makes it clear that it believes that trade should lead to outcomes that are inclusive and bring benefits to all stakeholders in Europe, posing the questions:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘How can EU trade policy ensure that the benefits of global value chains are shared by European producers, consumers and jobholders?’ </li>

<li>‘Are existing “flanking” policies sufficient to ensure that the benefits of trade are shared among different people and across different regions and markets in the EU?’ </li>

<li>‘How can the EU best ensure, where necessary, that trade and other policies play their part in helping people, sectors and communities adjust?’</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
EC, DG Trade, background document, ‘Public consultation on a future trade policy’, 2 June 2010<br />
<a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2010/june/tradoc_146220.pdf" target="_self">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2010/june/tradoc_146220.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The introductory question of the Commission’s consultation document implies a growing focus of EU trade policy on the EU’s near neighbours and ensuring complementarity with wider EU policies and objectives. It is unclear what implications these two trends will have for ACP-EU trade relations. Certainly the development of trade relations with ‘near neighbours’ is contributing to preference erosion, yet is also, as in the case of Moldova, potentially opening new avenues for the defence of non-reciprocal trade preferences not just for LDCs, but also for small and vulnerable ACP economies.</p><p>The EC’s analysis raises the question: if supply chains on which the EU depends are increasingly global, should not an international dimension be built into the EU’s evolving policy on the functioning of the food supply chain? This would appear to be particularly relevant given the EC policy emphasis on ensuring that trade leads to ‘outcomes which are inclusive and bring benefits to all stakeholders’. Given the close traditional ties between the EU and ACP agricultural sectors, it could be argued that this concept should therefore be extended outside the EU to encompass ACP-EU agricultural trade relationships.</p><p>The question of how EU trade policy should develop in the context of further CAP reforms and the EU’s objective of fostering a sustainable agricultural sector in the EU is a critical issue for the ACP, given that the CAP provided the basis for extensive preferences for ACP suppliers, while CAP reform in most sectors (with the exception of bananas) is the principal driving force behind the erosion of the value of traditional ACP agricultural trade preferences.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
